---
// Fig. 7 — The arc of four shares, 1901–2011.
// Purpose: the counter-narrative. The "Hindi belt exploded while the South
// restrained itself" frame only works if you squint at 1971→2011. Plotted
// across the full century, the North's share falls for the first seventy
// years, the South's peaks in 1951, and today's 46% for the Hindi belt is
// still below its 1901 level.
---

<figure class="chart-figure fourshares-figure">
  <figcaption class="fig-head">
    <span class="fig-label">Fig. 7</span>
    <span class="fig-title">The arc of four shares, 1901 → 2011</span>
    <span class="fig-unit">— per cent of India, by region —</span>
  </figcaption>
  <div id="fourshares-chart" class="chart fourshares-chart"></div>
  <p class="fig-note">
    <span class="hi">क्षेत्रीय हिस्सा, वक़्त के साथ</span> ·
    The North's share <b>fell</b> from <b>46.2%</b> in 1901 to a low of
    <b>41.9%</b> in 1971, before returning to <b>46.5%</b> in 2011 — still
    below its 1901 level. The South's share <em>peaked in 1951</em> at
    <b>26.1%</b> and has declined every census since.
  </p>
</figure>
